\bottomrule
\end{longtable}

The results demonstrate that all four fine-tuned models fail to meet the requirements for safe and accurate lay language conversion on this complex case. The most critical failure mode shared across all models is \textbf{hallucination of clinical content} — particularly the cause of death. This highlights a fundamental limitation of current fine-tuning approaches: models optimized for fluency and surface-level simplification do not inherently acquire the factual grounding necessary for clinical document conversion. Future work should explore retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), constrained decoding strategies, or larger instruction-tuned foundation models as base architectures to address these shortcomings.

